<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-01-09T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-01-09T18:00:00-05:00" n="977" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d977">
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-01-09T18:00:00-05:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">January 9, 1915, 6 p. m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>922. Your 1437, January 8. Department is advising commercial bodies and
                            telegraph companies to use, as far as possible, plain English words in
                            cable messages.</p>
                        <p>Can you arrange to have the senders of stopped messages immediately
                            informed so that there may be as little financial loss as possible?</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_BWJ1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>